		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2955179",
		"PostUrl" : "http://superuser.com/a/868759",
		"Site" : "superuser.com",
		"Title" : "For basic organizational purposes, compressing the folders on a per-clie...",
		"Body" : "<p>For basic organizational purposes, compressing the folders on a per-client basis\u2014or per-project basis\u2014simply makes it easier to reference the material later on. I generally divide up my client work folders between the generic, sundry stuff like notes and invoices. And then have code and related assets in another folder.</p>\n\n<p>I use Mac OS X and what I like to do is create an encrypted disk image using Apple\u2019s built-in \u201CDisk Utility\u201D for each client so I can safely take those files, archive them somewhere and not have to worry about prying eyes checking out file contents. Just create an image that is big enough to hold your files, choose an encrypting method\u2014I use 256-bit AES\u2014and create the disk. Then I store these images on an external hard drive I toss in a closet that is essentially my \u201Ccold storage\u201D for old client work; out of sight and out of mind. With hard drive prices getting cheaper, I have two of these project/client/work drives that are essentially mirrored backup copies of each other; I might not want to deal with these files but if I have to dust them off years down the line I want to make sure the data is recoverable in some way.</p>\n\n<p>Another benefit of archiving is you ensure that file metadata such as access and modification dates/times are retained. This might not seem like anything significant to you, but perhaps in the future you want to create a nice portfolio of your work and want to make sure you get the timeline right? Well, by having all of the files archived you are assured that none of the files had access or modification time/date stamps mucked around with either accidentally or intentionally. Also on the legal side of things, let\u2019s say something requires you to prove work you did was done a certain date/time? Having an archive with date/time stamps that are frozen you are in better shape when engaging in the nonsense some clients might engage in to blame you for something you might not have done.</p>\n\n<p>Performance-wise, I basically think that keeping unwanted, unneeded files on your \u201Clive system\u201D taking up space is a bad use of resources. My main system disk is about 50GB to 60GB in size. I only ever keep active client work on that. If I were to keep all client projects on my main hard drive, I would have 200GB to 300GB of dead weight just sitting there. Removing it from them main drive makes it easier for me to perform backups of the main hard drive. And it\u2019s made it easier and quicker to recover a backup if my system drive fails.</p>",

Shown here is driving a 60V motor (alternatives like <code>MAX15018</code>/<code>MAX15019</code> can also be used, but voltage won't get anywhere near as high as IR parts do.)</p>\n\n\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/rtVGG.png\" alt=\"schematic\"></p>\n\n\n\n<p><sup><a href=\"/plugins/schematics?image=http%3a%2f%2fi.stack.imgur.com%2frtVGG.png\">simulate this circuit</a></sup></p>",

		"PostUrl" : "http://communitybuilding.stackexchange.com/questions/999",
		"Site" : "communitybuilding.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "How can we encourage users to report misconduct correctly?",
		"Body" : "<p>I've encountered a subset of users in my subreddit that are interested in helping us curate content by reporting submissions that don't belong, but instead of using the <a href=\"http://www.reddit.com/wiki/reporting\" rel=\"nofollow\">reporting</a> feature, I've seen some of the following from various users:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li>Downvote the submission.</li>\n<li>Publicly berate the submitter in the comments.</li>\n<li>Ask the moderators to remove the post in the comments.</li>\n<li>Post a link to the user's profile in <a href=\"http://www.reddit.com/r/spam\" rel=\"nofollow\">/r/spam</a></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Some of these responses are appropriate, others not so much -- but even among those that are, I would prefer that they happen in conjunction with the user reporting the post to the subreddit moderators.  </p>\n\n<p><strong>Why is reporting useful?</strong></p>\n\n<p>Reporting is a reddit-wide feature that highlights the reported post to moderators of the subreddit it is in.  If a post is reported directly to the subreddit moderators, we can take action to prevent future misconduct at the subreddit level. We can monitor the offending user, block spammy domains so the user can't create new accounts to continue spamming, etc.  We even have some automation in place that escalates notifications to moderators after a certain number of reports on a post, and automatically removes a post after a much higher threshold.  </p>\n\n<p><strong>The problem:</strong></p>\n\n<p>Users seem to be interested in reporting bad content to <em>somebody</em>, but either don't know the established procedure in our subreddit (trope: <em>nobody <a href=\"http://www.reddit.com/r/all/search?q=%22read%20the%20sidebar%22&sort=relevance&t=all\" rel=\"nofollow\">reads the sidebar</a></em>) or, in the case of spammers, supersede us in favor of the script at /r/spam.</p>\n\n<p>I'm not sure that there's a solution here that can be applied in a single stroke, but I am interested in changing the culture of our subreddit so that users are encouraged to use the reporting feature. Is there any way I can do a better job of conveying to our users that reporting is useful to the moderators, aside from the default literature and functionality that Reddit provides?</p>",

		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2955075",

		"Title" : "Well It seems fairly obvious by the way it reads. If you just take the w...",
		"Body" : "<p>Well It seems fairly obvious by the way it reads. If you just take the whole thing at face value, then it doesn't start at Romans 6:1, it goes back before that. 6:1 begins with a question based on what he just said, which goes back to chapter 4. Righteousness is imputed by simply believing what God says, not because of what we experience, but in spite of what is experienced (when Abraham was 99 years old and it was impossible to fulfill God's promise, he believed God anyway...in spite of what he saw/experienced, etc.), which takes us back to chapter 3 and imputed righteousness by faith (simply believing God). That then becomes the premise moving forward, faith...not experience, believing God. </p>\n\n<p>You simply believe God and take him at his word. He lists a bunch of good stuff in 5 which we receive by faith, even undoing what Adam brought. So much is this true, so great is our salvation, so sure our justification, that it might be concluded that we can do whatever we want now that we are saved and still be good with God. Hence the beginning of chapter 6...based on everything that has come before it. </p>\n\n<p>The assumption in 6 is that a Christian will not continue in sin because the Christian has been baptized into Christ's body, been put to death with Christ, put in the grave with Christ and has raised again unto new life. He uses the example of two seeds being planted into the ground together. We are challenged to believe this just like Abraham believed God could still produce seed when his body was now dead at 99 years old. He believed God even though it was hard to believe, in fact, it was contrary to his experience. \"He stumbled not at the promises of God, but was strong in faith, giving glory to God.\" So should we be, in chapter 6 and believe that God says our flesh is dead and, as a result, we are free from sin.</p>\n\n<p>He finishes out 6 without a shadow of a doubt that the old man is dead, saying three times that we are free from sin. Then he moves into 7 with a statement followed by an analogy. He says, if you are dead (like we are in Romans 6) then we are free from the law. Just like a woman who is married to a mean old man wanted to be free from him but could not break the law. Her old man had to die for her to be free to marry the new man. Notice the law did not die, the old man did. Hence, the old man is dead and we are free from him completely (as the law ends at the grave).</p>\n\n<p>This continues perfectly in past tense language, bringing in the law as an example, using himself before Christ. This goes down to verse 14. Here he switches language to draw a point. What happens when a person tries to please God by the law? This whole argument is about a religious person under the law trying to live up to it, the harder you try the worse it gets, the more guilt you feel for failing. After verse 14 he uses himself in past tense language as if he were still a religious person trying to live up to it, wanting to be free from the power of the flesh (which was put to death in chapter 6). </p>\n\n<p>Why would he do this? Because he was the poster child of good religious guy. This is not Paul currently, this is Paul using past tense language to describe the futility of trying to please God through good works.</p>\n\n<p>In verse 24 and 25, he asks the question, \"who shall deliver me from the BODY of this death?\" he recognizes the problem is the body...the flesh...that thing which was put to death in chapter 6. He answers it... \"I thank God through Jesus Christ our Lord.\" He did it, the fight is over. </p>\n\n<p>To confirm this interpretation, he continues into chapter 8 with this statement, which would seem strange if Paul, was still in the condition described in chapter 7. He says:</p>\n\n<p>Romans 8:1-8  There is therefore now no condemnation to them which are in Christ Jesus, who walk not after the flesh, but after the Spirit. For the law of the Spirit of life in Christ Jesus hath made me free from the law of sin and death. For what the law could not do, in that it was weak through the flesh, God sending his own Son in the likeness of sinful flesh, and for sin, condemned sin in the flesh: That the righteousness of the law might be fulfilled in us, who walk not after the flesh, but after the Spirit. For they that are after the flesh do mind the things of the flesh; but they that are after the Spirit the things of the Spirit. For to be carnally minded is death; but to be spiritually minded is life and peace. Because the carnal mind is enmity against God: for it is not subject to the law of God, neither indeed can be. <strong>So then they that are in the flesh cannot please God.</strong></p>\n\n<p>They that are in the flesh cannot please God! That's the problem with the guy in chapter 7, he was still in the flesh..so he could not please God. But 6, most of 7, and 8 all say that the Christian is not in the flesh. </p>\n\n<p>Now, think about this. If Paul existed, as a Christian, in chapter 7, then he said he could not EVER control himself. In fact, every time he tried to, he failed. He just could not do the right thing! He knew what the right thing was, but he just couldn't do it...ALL THE TIME! \"For that which I do I allow not: for what I would, that do I not; but what I hate, that do I.\" Really? Are you that way? Can you never do the right thing?</p>\n\n<p>That is not the prison on death row saying that, that is the Apostle to the gentiles. the writer of most of the books of the NT, the great Paul. </p>\n\n<p>All through the book of Romans he uses the same thought continually. It would be very strange to say that he suddenly switches and contradicts himself for about 10 verses and then goes right back to his original argument. A better thought would be that he simply used language to prove his point that a man outside of Christ who is trying to live up to a law to earn his salvation cannot do it. It is only through Christ that he has hope of pleasing God.</p>",

We are no longer slaves to sin, but are slaves to God and righteousness.</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Romans 6:16-18 (ESV) Do you not know that if you present yourselves to anyone as obedient slaves, you are slaves of the one whom you obey, either of sin, which leads to death, or of obedience, which leads to righteousness? But thanks be to God, that you who were once slaves of sin have become obedient from the heart to the standard of teaching to which you were committed, and, having been set free from sin, have become slaves of righteousness.</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Answer</strong></p>\n\n<p>Knowing what sin is and its consequences, you are set free. The Pharisees did not even know that their behaviour was sin.</p>\n\n<p><strong>However, I don't think many Christians would say that they feel very free from sin. In fact, Paul goes on in the next chapter to say that he is a slave to sin.</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>Romans 7:18-19 (ESV) For I know that nothing good dwells in me, that is, in my flesh. For I have the desire to do what is right, but not the ability to carry it out. For I do not do the good I want, but the evil I do not want is what I keep on doing.</strong></p>\n\n<p><strong>This kind of language doesn't sound very \"free\". If he says that Christians are \"slaves of the one whom you obey\", and yet he finds himself obeying the flesh, doesn't that make him a slave to sin? 		"Title" : "Was just reading the similar verse in Luke and was drawn into it too...\n...",
		"Body" : "<p>Was just reading the similar verse in Luke and was drawn into it too...</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>For I say unto you, That unto every one which hath shall be given; and from him that hath not, even that he hath shall be taken away from him. (Luke 19:26, KJV)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The Luke version appears to add some helpful context, so I suggest reading that chapter.  A few directions that seemed to have some sort of foundation...</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>The Luke version of the verse comes at the end of parable about the stewardship the nobleman's servants choose while he was away.  10 servants are all given the same amount of money.  When the nobleman returns, he asks what has been done with it.\nOne man traded diligently and turned it into 10.\nAnother turned it into 5.\nBut one stashed it away in fear of the nobleman.\nAt the end, the coin he had kept is taken away from him and given to the one who gained up to 10.</p>\n\n<p>So one thought that comes forward to me is that it may relate to courage\\faith\\understanding.</p>\n\n<p>Because the descriptions in Luke emphasize that the servant did nothing because of his fear.  A fear of the nobleman as much as anything.  Because he is \"austere\" and productive.  Those who had faith went out and used it and got more.  Those who didn't lost what they they had.\nUnderstanding is a bigger picture that may fit because understanding is centered upon fear of the Lord (e.g. Prov 1:7)... which would then really put the Matthew 13:12 into more context coming from:</p></li>\n</ul>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>And the disciples came, and said unto him, Why speakest thou unto them in parables? 11He answered and said unto them, Because it is given unto you to know the mysteries of the kingdom of heaven, but to them it is not given. (Mat 13:10-11, KJV)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<ul>\n<li><p>A second avenue of consideration comes from the words introducing the whole parable...</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>And as they heard these things, he added and spake a parable, because he was nigh to Jerusalem, and because they thought that the kingdom of God should immediately appear. (Luke 19:11)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The parable in Luke suggests that the nobleman <em>expected</em> gains from trading.  And his criticism was that the servant could have at least gotten some gain just by putting it in the bank.</p>\n\n<p>Because His point here is that the Kingdom isn't immediately coming, it follows that this is a message to them of what they should be doing going forward.  Not keeping their light hidden, but going forth in service and evangelism as He had displayed to them.  That being fully happy to sit on one's faith feeling secure suggests maybe one doesn't have the faith in Jesus\\God, the repentance of putting oneself first, that such faith would be.</p></li>\n<li><p>A third connection may start in the situation just before the parable in Luke 19, and may have motivated it.  Zacchaeus the tax collector was rich.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>And when they saw it, they all murmured, saying, That he was gone to be guest with a man that is a sinner. (Luke 19:7, KJV)</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>And this is given just after Luke 18:18-27, where Jesus speaks of how very hard it is for the rich people to enter Heaven, being harder than passing a camel through the eye of a needle.  So could this verse\\parable also serve to remind us not to look on men by what they have, but by who they are?  That we must be careful not to judge men by their appearance, by who they are financially, but by what they do.  If nothing else, a reminder at least that men of any class can be saved, and does deserve real effort from believers as well.  And in Matthew 13:8, it does echo some of the same leadin, saying some brought forth an hundredfold, some sixtyfold, some thirtyfold.</p></li>\n<li><p>And one final connection that really catches me perhaps most...the idea that if you fight to hold onto what you cannot keep (your life), you lose even it.  If you give up your life to Him,  then you life a life with purpose now, and life everlasting to come. I believe Paul or Peter says something very similar to this in one of their letters, but I cannot find it unfortunately.</p>\n\n<p>The servant thinks he has held onto something. He has, by his reasoning, seemingly made himself safe from failure.  But he held onto what was never his to begin with (the coin that the nobleman had given him, in the Luke verse).  Echoed in the verse</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>For whosoever will save his life shall lose it: and whosoever will lose his life for my sake shall find it. (Mat 16:25, KJV)</p>\n</blockquote></li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Of the four, the riches connection perhaps makes me the most unsettled.  The support noted in Matthew doesn't seem solid, and nothing else in the surrounding context there seems to supports it.  But maybe the failing is on me to be secured in the message of not judging by appearance that is certainly given other places in the Bible (James 2, John 7, Luke 15, etc).\nBut, all four messages seem to have some support to them.  And perhaps tie together in the end.  But, regardless, I hope I didn't detour your question too much, haven't ENTIRELY talked your ears off, and have added some helpful thoughts.  Thanks for your time :-)</p>",

		"Title" : "One way to do this (and yes, it is ugly and hackish) is to create a cust...",
		"Body" : "<p>One way to do this (and yes, it is ugly and hackish) is to create a custom page having a custom page template that draws out all of your posts and creates the proper admin url links for each one.</p>\n\n<p>For example:</p>\n\n<pre><code><?php\n/*\nTemplate Name: View Posts Quickly\n*/\nif ( !is_user_logged_in() ) {\n   # Redirect the user or use wp_die('Permission denied') or throw a 404\n} else if ( !current_user_can('activate_plugins') ) {\n   # Permission denied\n} else {\n   $query_args = array(\n      'post_type' => 'post',\n      'posts_per_page' => '-1',\n      'post_status' => array( 'any' ),\n      'orderby' => 'title',\n      'order' => 'asc'\n   );\n   $post_list = new WP_Query( $query_args );\n   if ( ! $post_list->have_posts() ) {\n      # Tell user no posts found\n   } else {\n      echo '<h2>The Post List:</h2><ul>';\n      while ( $post_list->have_posts() ) {\n         $current = $post_list->next_post();\n\n         # Modify the below to include any extra data wanted for each item\n         echo get_post_edit_link( $current->post_title, '<li>', '</li>', $current->ID);\n      }\n      echo '</ul>';\n   }\n}\n?>\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>Obviously the above could be turned into an actual admin page if wanted. I do it on my own sites when I want to have a very different view of things on the back end.</p>\n\n<p>Using the above (and, of course, creating a private page and setting the template to use the above template) will get one a cleaner, faster list.</p>\n\n<p>But the normal display of wordpress posts displays a lot of extra data using a lot of extra queries due to the database design. The db design gives good flexibility, but one trade off is the ability to draw lots of related information in just one or two queries.</p>\n\n<p>A better way might be to kill those extra queries by stripping out the term columns displayed in the post list (but you would lose the various sorting, limiting, etc. tools that the wordpress list gives, though you could build your own filters, sorting, etc. in as wanted) using the <code>manage_*_posts_columns</code> filter.</p>",

		"Title" : "As a mechanic with many years of experience there are only a couple of w...",
		"Body" : "<p>As a mechanic with many years of experience there are only a couple of ways engine oil can enter the coolant system 1. Some idiot added oil to the coolant overflow tank or radiator. 2. A crack in between an oil gallery and a coolant passage either in the engine block or the cylinder head(s). There could be some other reasons but it has been my experience that if you have oil in the water you have a serious problem because oil pressure is higher than coolant pressure except with a hot engine that is turned off and in that case you'll have some water in the oil as well but if you have a crack in one or both of the heads above the coolant level (with the engine off) then only a trace amount of moisture will cross over and will usually be evaporated by engine temps. Take my advice, drive em like you stole em and when they won't take anymore scrap em</p>",

		"Title" : "Help with notation for the state of a dynamical system defined by a PDE",
		"Body" : "<p>Before my question let me briefly describe a simplified version of the dynamical system I'm working with. Suppose that I have a density function $m(\\boldsymbol{x},t)$, that describes the abundance of some quantity in a vector space $\\Omega = [a,b]^{n}$. Now suppose that the density at each point in vector space changes over time, with a rate that may be dependent on the presence/absence of density at every other point in space</p>\n\n<p>$$\n\\partial_{t}m(\\boldsymbol{x},t) = m(\\boldsymbol{x},t)F(\\boldsymbol{x},?),\n$$</p>\n\n<p>where $F$ might be something like</p>\n\n<p>$$\nF(\\boldsymbol{x},?) = \\int_{\\Omega} m(\\boldsymbol{y},t) k(\\boldsymbol{x}, \\boldsymbol{y}) \\; d\\boldsymbol{y}\n$$</p>\n\n<p>i.e. a function of the focal point of interest $\\boldsymbol{x}$ and all other different points $\\boldsymbol{y}$ in vector space, where $k$ is some kind of kernal(?). </p>\n\n<p><strong>Question 1</strong>: \nWhat notation should I use to refer to the state of the system over the whole space? What should replace my question mark in $F(\\boldsymbol{x},?)$, should it be $F(\\boldsymbol{x},m)$, or maybe $F(\\boldsymbol{x},\\Omega)$, or something else? </p>\n\n<p><strong>Question 2</strong>: \nI have an extended part to this question that I'm not even really sure how to explain. Suppose I now have multiple dynamical systems like the one just described, and a second 'higher order' density function $M(?,t)$, that describes the abundance of each dynamical system in some other kind of space. What would the notation for that look like? How would I refer to a particular dynamical system (i.e. the question mark again), what would the space be, etc.? Essentially, I'm interested in whether I could formulate a dynamical equation that is analogous to a hyperbolic PDE, but one in which the flux of the density $M$ is no longer defined by a finite system of ODEs, but by an infinite number of PDEs. </p>\n\n<p>PS I apologise if the first question is stupid, and the second question doesn't make any sense. I don't really have any formal mathematical training, but I'm desperate to get to grips with this kind maths for possible use in my PhD. Any advice or links would be much appreciated. </p>",

		"Body" : "<blockquote>\n  <p>When a program starts it has fixed data structures with fixed data</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>This is a bit of a misconception. It has a fixed form and a fixed set of rewrite rules but these rewrite rules can explode into something much larger. For instance the expression [1..100000000] in Haskell is represented by a very small amount of code but its normal form is massive.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>One can't add new data to these structures</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Yes and no. The purely functional subset of a language like Haskell or ML can't get data from the outside world but any language for practical programming has a mechanism for inserting data from the outside world into the purely functional subset. In Haskell this is done very carefully but in ML you can do this when ever you want.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>There are no variables in the code</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>This is pretty much true but don't confuse this with the idea that nothing can be named. You name useful expressions all the time and constantly reuse them. Also both ML and Haskell, every lisp I have tried, and hybrids like scala, all have a means of creating variables. They just are not commonly used. And again the purely functional subsets of such languages don't have them.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>You can merely \"copy\" from the already data or currently calculated\n  data</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>You can preform calcultion by reduction to normal form. The best thing to do is probably to go write programs in a functional language to see how they do in fact preform calculations.</p>\n\n<p>For instance \"sum [1..1000]\" is not a calculation I want to preform but it is quite handily done by Haskell. We gave it a small expression that had meaning to us and haskell gave us out the corresponding number. So it defiantly preforms calculation. </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>If data structures are supposed to remain as they are (immutable), how the hell does someone add a new item in a list?</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>You don't add a new item to a list, you create a new list out of the old one. Because the old one can't be mutated it is perfectly safe to use it in the new list, or where ever else you want. Much more data can be safely shared in this schema.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>What is the point in having a program that can't get new data? Say you\n  have a sensor attached to your computer that wants to feed data to the\n  program. Would that mean that we can't store the incoming data\n  anywhere?</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>As far as user input goes, any practical programming language has a way of getting user input. This happens. However there is a fully functional subset of these languages that you write most of your code in and you reap the advantages in this way.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>How is functional programming good for machine learning in that case?\n  Since machine learning builds from the assumption of updating the\n  program's \"perception\" of things - thus storing new data.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>This would be the case for active learning but most machine learning I have worked with (I work as a code monkey in a machine learning group and have done so for a few years) has a one time learning process where all the training data is loaded in at once. But for active learning you can't do things 100% purely functionally. You are going to have to read in some data from the outside world.</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2954487",
		"PostUrl" : "http://physics.stackexchange.com/a/160928",
		"Site" : "physics.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "At first, the $i \\epsilon$ prescription: In Feynman diagrams we have a l...",
		"Body" : "<p>At first, the $i \\epsilon$ prescription: In Feynman diagrams we have a lot of Green's functions connected by some rules, the Feynman rules. Actually, the $i \\epsilon$ prescription is more related to the Green's function. The prescription is responsible for a choice in the boundary conditions (asymptotic behaviour). We may put this $i \\epsilon$ inside the expression $(\\omega + i \\epsilon)^2$ or $(\\omega - i \\epsilon)^2$. The first is related to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propagator#Retarded_propagator\" rel=\"nofollow\">retarded Green's function</a>, the second is related to <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propagator#Advanced_propagator\" rel=\"nofollow\">advanced Green's function</a>.  This choices of boundary condition are related to some adapted Feynman's rules. Calculating things in this prescriptions is not manifest relativistically and not so compact. The <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Propagator#Feynman_propagator\" rel=\"nofollow\">Feynman Green's function</a> is the best for doing calculations and very natural.</p>\n\n<p>Now, let's be more general. This prescriptions are aroused when we have operators like this:</p>\n\n<p>$$\n(H-E)G(t)=\\delta(t)\n$$</p>\n\n<p>We want to find an expression for $G(t)$. Applying Fourier transform, we can find that</p>\n\n<p>$$\nG(x) = \\frac{1}{(2 \\pi)} \\int d\\omega \\, \\frac{e^{-ip(t)}}{\\omega - E\\pm i\\varepsilon}\n$$</p>\n\n<p>If you see this function in complex plane, we can se that we have a cut in real axis made by eigenvalues of $H$. The prescription $\\epsilon$ determine how far we pass about the singularity $\\omega=E$. The choice of signal tell in what side.</p>\n\n<p>This precription is simply procedure to getting inverse of operators with real eigenvalues, satisfying some asymptotic behavior. </p>\n\n<p>We can interpret this $\\epsilon$ as a inverse of timelife of the signal describe by the repective Green's funciton. This is because we can identify a <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Relativistic_Breit%E2%80%93Wigner_distribution\" rel=\"nofollow\">relativistic Breit\u2013Wigner distribution</a></p>\n\n<p>The untary is hold because we get $\\epsilon \\rightarrow 0$, so the signal persist at infinite time.</p>\n\n<p>The adiabatic turn on and turn off interaction is another mathematical departure: adiabatic theorem and <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gell-Mann_and_Low_theorem\" rel=\"nofollow\">Gell-mann and Low theorem</a>, but physically is very close to the $i\\epsilon$. Is a inverse of a caracteristic time that is send to infinity. </p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2954477",
		"PostUrl" : "http://chemistry.stackexchange.com/a/24120",
		"Site" : "chemistry.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "A redox reaction is any reaction in which oxidation and reduction are oc...",
		"Body" : "<p>A redox reaction is any reaction in which oxidation and reduction are occurring. The word redox is a portmanteau of REDuction-OXidation. So, if we can correctly identify reduction and oxidation, we can identify redox reactants. In practice, this can be a little challenging, so I will focus first on the second part of your questions (definitions) and then go back to the reaction.</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Ionization is any process that produces ions. </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The conversion of a hydrogen atom to a hydrogen ion by loss of an electron is an ionization. \n$$\\ce{H -> H+ + e-}$$\nSo to is the reaction of hydrochloric acid and water, which produces hydronium ions and chloride ions.\n$$\\ce{HCl + H2O -> Cl- + H3O+}$$</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Oxidation is a loss of electrons.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The ionization of hydrogen atoms to hydrogen ions is an oxidation.\n$$\\ce{H -> H+ + e-}$$</p>\n\n<p>So to is the conversion of carbon monoxide to carbon dioxide:</p>\n\n<p>$$\\ce{2CO + O2 -> 2CO2}$$</p>\n\n<p>Note that this type of reaction is what gave us the word oxidation - compounds are reacting with oxygen and atoms end up with more oxygen atoms bound to them. </p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Reduction is a gain of electrons.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>The ionization of chlorine atoms to chloride ions is a reduction.</p>\n\n<p>$$\\ce{Cl + e- -> Cl-}$$</p>\n\n<p>So too is the conversions of acetylene to ethane:</p>\n\n<p>$$\\ce{C2H2 + 2H2 -> C2H6}$$</p>\n\n<p>Not all oxidations and reductions are ionizations. There is a simple mnemonic in English for remembering oxidation and reduction: OIL RIG (Oxidation Is Loss Reduction Is Gain).</p>\n\n<blockquote>\n  <p>Oxidation and reduction happen together. </p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>In principle we can write an equation that shows only oxidation:</p>\n\n<p>$$\\ce{H -> H+ + e-}$$</p>\n\n<p>but oxidation cannot happen on its own. That electron that was lost needs to be picked up by something else. This reaction that shows only oxidation is called a \"half-reaction\" and needs to be coupled with a reduction half-reaction to show a valid chemical reaction:</p>\n\n<p>$$\\ce{H -> H+ + e-}$$\n$$\\ce{Cl + e- -> Cl-}$$\n$$\\ce{H + Cl ->HCl}$$</p>\n\n<p>In the other examples I gave, both processes are occurring. In the oxidation of carbon monoxide, the oxygen molecules are being reduced.</p>\n\n<p>The surest way to identify oxidation and reduction (and thus redox) is to compare the oxidation states of the reactants and the products. Determining oxidation states/numbers is more complex that I want to put here, so start with the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Oxidation_state#Determining_the_oxidation_state_or_number\" rel=\"nofollow\">Wikipedia article</a>.</p>\n\n<p>For the carbon monoxide example:</p>\n\n<pre><code>                  reactants    products\nC                 +2           +4\nO (bonded to C)   -2           -2\nO2                0            -2\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The carbon atoms are being oxidized (oxidation number increased) and the oxygen atoms in $\\ce{O2}$ are being reduced (oxidation number decreases). The oxygen atom already attached to carbon did not change its oxidation number.</p>",
		"TimeStamp" : "2015-01-24T14:03:07.137Z",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2954464",
		"PostUrl" : "http://physics.stackexchange.com/a/56410",
		"Site" : "physics.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "I'm not a physicist, rather a simple engineering student, and I believe ...",
		"Body" : "<p>I'm not a physicist, rather a simple engineering student, and I believe your confusion has confused me, too. That's great, because it made me look for the answers myself. This is just my personal guess (though grounded in some fact), but it makes a lot of sense to me, and I hope it makes sense to you, too.</p>\n\n<p>Bear with me if this is a long answer.</p>\n\n<p>First off, when we speak of the difference in the amount of electrons just before and just after a resistor, you're right: there is fundamentally no difference in the number of electrons. We know this because all the electrons (current) that comes in must be equal to the number of electrons (current) that comes out. This is one of Kirchoff's laws. Moreover, we know that matter doesn't just disappear and it isn't being converted into energy, either.</p>\n\n<p>Of course, the second of Kirchoff's laws tell us that the sum of all the voltages in a circuit must be zero (so, in a simple circuit, the initial voltage from the battery minus all the voltage drops from all the resistors is zero). That tells us that something must already be happening within those resistors that has nothing to do with the battery. So that's a good start.</p>\n\n<p>Then, we should also understand that current and voltage are not the same thing. That is, if you <em>already</em> have a flowing current, that current does not have its own voltage. You might need voltage to jumpstart the flow of current, but once it's already flowing, the current exists as the jumping of one electron across ions, and each electron is only a single point -- it doesn't have voltage because it's only one point. More importantly, current flows uniformly, so there is no voltage that is being generated as it does flow. Whether it is just before or just after the resistor, the current is the same there, and it produces no voltage.</p>\n\n<p>Here's a drawing I made for you:</p>\n\n<p><img src=\"http://i.stack.imgur.com/Z3hH3.png\" alt=\"Drawing of current\"></p>\n\n<p>I drew it as it really is, against the convention. Notice that, despite there being a pre-existing voltage difference between the two batteries, the distribution of electrons is uniform. So, if you tried to take a voltage difference between the first electron and the fourth electron, you get a voltage difference of zero, <em>even if they are flowing</em>, because their distribution will continue being uniform. This, I think, is the equivalent of measuring the voltage across a wire with no resistor.</p>\n\n<p>Because I think it will be useful in analyzing what happens across the resistor, I'd like to point out that the battery is the initial source of voltage. It's made so that one end is much more electronegative than the other, and that one pole has a large supply of electrons whereas the other has a large deficit. So, if you link the two ends together, the electrons flow from the less electronegative end (with more electrons) to the more electronegative end (with less electrons). In the process, the difference in electrons from pole to pole equalizes. Moreover, the chemical reactions happening inside the battery make it so that the poles (anode for negative, cathode for positive) degrade both cathode and anode -- unless it's a rechargeable battery, in which case this reaction is reversible.</p>\n\n<p>But that doesn't quite spell out why there is a voltage drop across the load. If the voltage difference exists between the poles, then shouldn't the same voltage difference exist all throughout the circuit? The answer seems to be yes... but only if there is no load.</p>\n\n<p>So, we have to go back and ask, what is a voltage drop, and where does it come from?</p>\n\n<p>I think your question really is, what happens to the energy at a molecular level? It doesn't just disappear. When the voltage drops, what does it mean? If the same amount of electrons enter the resistor and then leave it, doesn't their energy stay the same?</p>\n\n<p>First, we know that if their energies are the same, then the voltmeter will tell us there is no voltage. We also know that, if their energies are the same, there is no difference between the two points. And finally, if their energies are the same, we know that no energy was lost, and therefore, no work was taken out of the system.</p>\n\n<p>But we <em>do</em> know that work was taken out of the system, and we can see the voltmeter giving us a reading. But if the number of electrons is the same across the resistor, then there <strong>must</strong> be energy being lost. But, where did that energy come from?</p>\n\n<p>We go back to what voltage is -- it is the amount of energy per unit charge. One unit of charge is the electron. So voltage is just the measure of how much energy each electron carries. There are two separate energies in the electron -- its rest energy and its momentum energy. Its rest energy is constant, but its momentum energy is definitely not.</p>\n\n<p>An electron carries energy by its orbital and shell. That is, the more energy an electron has, the higher up it goes into its shell. I think this is because it has more kinetic energy, so it tends to move faster. Moving faster causes it to occupy a larger volume, and so for the nucleus to keep the electron, there must be more pull to keep it in place. I'm imagining it's like the orbit of a planet around the sun, where wider orbits signify more total energy in the system. The orbitals are (I'm guessing, but fairly certain) caused by the discrete nature of energy -- photons are the most irreducible form of energy, so an electron can only jump between orbitals by discrete amounts.</p>\n\n<p>So, inside the battery, the electrons feel a potential difference between the different poles of the battery. This potential difference imparts energy into the electron, causing it to jump to a higher orbital. It then travels through the atoms in the wire until it reaches the resistor.</p>\n\n<p>Inside the resistor, energy is taken out of the electron. The electron jumps to a smaller orbital, and in the process it releases a photon. This release of a photon means it has given off energy. The photon, having energy, is converted to work and waste.</p>\n\n<p>The electrons, now occupying a smaller orbital, exits the resistor with less energy.Because their energy is smaller, their voltage drops. And this, I think, is the reason why it is called a <strong>voltage drop</strong>.</p>\n\n<p>This answer raises the question, though -- how does a voltmeter detect this voltage drop, if it occurs in the orbital shells of an atom? And the answer is interesting: it doesn't. At least, not directly.</p>\n\n<p>From what I can read, what voltmeters do is measure the deflection of a pointer against a spring. The pointer, in turn, is moved by the repulsive forces of the electrons on a pivoting wheel inside the voltmeter. And the repulsive forces is, of course, directly proportional to the amount of energy inside the electrons. Because we know the equations of energy, all this is calibrated. What the voltmeter actually measures is not the voltage itself, but rather the force that the voltage difference exerts on the pointer of the voltmeter.</p>\n\n<p>I can't say much more on how the voltmeter works. I'm frankly not so sure if that's true, but I know that the moving current with a certain voltage must work in some way like I just said.</p>\n\n<p>When the electron comes back home to the cathode (because we're thinking in terms of actual electrons moving, rather than the conventional electron holes moving), its voltage will not be zero, but rather will be equal to the energy per eletron in the cathode. Kirchoff's law tells us that at every load, the voltage difference decreases due to the voltage drop. Because the electrons still have energy inside the cathode, this doesn't mean the voltage is zero there (causing electrons to have no energy, which intuitively makes them have no momentum, which can't be true). It just means that the energy when the electron comes back is now the same as the energy at the cathode, so there is no more potential difference and the journey of the electron stops.</p>\n\n<p>If I've made any glaring errors here (and I'm bound to have, as most of this is me guessing and trying to make sense of what I know), please feel free to edit me. And if I mis-explained something, please point out where in a comment, so I and everybody else can see where it's wrong and why. Thank you!</p>\n\n<p>EDIT: I realize I used voltage in two ways here: the difference in potential between two points, and the energy per unit charge. One definition requires two points to be defined, whereas one requires only one point.</p>\n\n<p>I think we can reconcile this by imagining that there is the same voltage everywhere. Each electron has exactly the same amount of energy. In such a case, there is no voltage difference. There is no potential difference, meaning there is no gradient which will cause the electrons to move.</p>\n\n<p>So I guess I'm saying, voltage can be a point quantity, whereas the potential difference, or voltage difference, requires two points to be defined. Certainly, this is consistent with the definitions of voltage (and as I remember in class, voltage by itself is a scalar, so it only requires itself to be defined, not another point; the gradient or difference is what requires another point).</p>",

		"Site" : "philosophy.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "He writes here that it's 'utterly absurd' that the circles would be equa...",
		"Body" : "<p>He writes here that it's 'utterly absurd' that the circles would be equal, because then, if we would split a cone up in as many partitions as possible, and reconstruct it, we would have a cylinder - which would then mean that a cylinder and a cone are essentially equivalent, which they are not.</p>\n\n<p>Since the circles can <em>not</em> be equal, they must be unequal. From the first part of the quote, it can be understood that therefrom follows that 'a cone is composed of many breaks and protrusions like steps'.</p>\n\n<p>The underlying problem here is that math doesn't talk about the real world. </p>\n\n<p>Suppose we have a function <em>d : [0, 10] \u2192 R</em>\u00A0 with \u00A0<em>d(h) = h</em>\u00A0 for the diameter of the cone on a specific height. Then cutting the cone on height <em>h<sub>1</sub></em> would mean looking at <em>d' : [0, h<sub>1</sub>]</em> \u00A0 and \u00A0 <em>d'' : (h<sub>1</sub>,10]</em> \u00A0 (note the open-closed interval here), where again <em>d'(h)=h</em> \u00A0 and \u00A0 <em>d''(h)=h</em>. Surely the highest point of <em>d'</em> is not equal to the lowest point of <em>d''</em>: <em>d'</em> includes <em>h<sub>1</sub></em> in the domain, while <em>d''</em> doesn't. </p>\n\n<p>However, the conclusion Democritus draws from this, that 'a cone is composed of many breaks and protrusions like steps', is incorrect: the function <em>d</em> is a smooth function. This is because Democritus mixes up math and the real world.</p>",

		"Title" : "Thanks to the @egreg 's answer I found an easier solution :\n\nadd $ +\\fra...",
		"Body" : "<p>Thanks to the @egreg 's answer I found an easier solution :</p>\n\n<p>add $ +\\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{4}$ we have :\n$$y = x + \\sqrt{x}  +\\frac{1}{4} - \\frac{1}{4}$$\nthen :\n$$y=(\\sqrt{x}+\\frac{1}{2})^2-\\frac{1}{4}$$\n$\\sqrt{x} + \\frac{1}{2}$ is clearly positive so :\n$$(\\sqrt{y+{\\frac{1}{4}}}-\\frac{1}{2})^2=x$$\nthen : \n$$x = y + \\frac{1}{2}-\\sqrt{y+{\\frac{1}{4}}}$$\nyou can swap x and y to have the inverse function.</p>\n\n<blockquote class=\"spoiler\">\n  <p> Because the range of the function is $y \u2265 0$ we have $x \u2265 0$ for the inverse function domain.</p>\n</blockquote>\n\n<p>Which is equal to this answer <a href=\"http://math.stackexchange.com/a/1116697/208741\">http://math.stackexchange.com/a/1116697/208741</a></p>",

I ask, \"What fraction are red?\" Hopefully someone says $frac{1}{2}$ and we can discuss the misconception.  In terms of how to relate $frac{1}{2}$ to the ratio 1:2 I do it after establishing the equivalence of ratio by scaling up both sides. I want to make green from blue and yellow in the ratio 1:2. I have 2 tins of blue how many yellow? Students often say that's easy just double the tins of yellow because you have doubled the blue. Now I ask them if I had 1000 blue or something like they say 500 but this time because they recognise there are $frac{1}{2}$ the number of blue. A subtle change but one that recognise the proportion of blue and yellow is the same for equivalent ratios. Hope this helps.</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2954395",
		"PostUrl" : "http://physics.stackexchange.com/a/106122",
		"Site" : "physics.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "While grinding metal, sparks are produced because of Friction. The rotat...",
		"Body" : "<p>While grinding metal, sparks are produced because of <strong>Friction</strong>. The rotating grinder cuts through the metal molecules, rubbing against them and producing heat. Some particles get loose in this process and burn because of this heat.</p>\n\n<p>From Wikipedia, \"<em>Steel is an alloy of iron, with carbon being the primary alloying element, up to 2.1% by weight. Carbon, other elements, and inclusions within iron act as hardening agents that prevent the movement of dislocations that naturally exist in the iron atom crystal lattices. Varying the amount of alloying elements, their form in the steel either as solute elements, or a precipitated phases, retards the movement of those dislocations that make iron so ductile and so weak, and so it controls qualities such as the hardness, ductility, and tensile strength of the resulting steel.</em>\"</p>\n\n<p>In other words, Steel gets its strength because of the carbon impurities in its lattice. So obviously, Steel is much more stronger than Iron. Aluminium on the other hand is even softer and lighter than Iron, so there's even lesser friction and hence, lesser sparks. There is also the point about rusting and Aluminium does not rust. Though I am not sure if this is directly related to the production of sparks.</p>",

		"Title" : "This happened to me after changing my login password. I fixed it thanks ...",
		"Body" : "<p>This happened to me after changing my login password. I fixed it thanks to article on Apple support: <a href=\"https://discussions.apple.com/thread/6724601\" rel=\"nofollow\">https://discussions.apple.com/thread/6724601</a></p>\n\n<p>Simply I had to change password for my \"login\" keychain.</p>\n\n<p>But I was asked to input password to open \"Local items\" keychain. I solved that issue exactly according this post: <a href=\"http://support.apple.com/en-us/HT203897\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://support.apple.com/en-us/HT203897</a>\nYou need to open folder ~/Library/Keychains/, find and delete folder with name similar to \"A8F5E7B8-CEC1-4479-A7DF-F23CB076C8B8\" and restart your Mac immediately.</p>\n\n<p>I had to fixed both \"login\" and \"Local items\" prompt to solve it. Only changing password for \"login\" keychain seemed not to work although it should according Apple support. But I haven't test it heavily. </p>\n\n<p>Hope it helps.</p>",

		"Title" : "So, by your definition, you want not just a Ghost, but an Apparition: a ...",
		"Body" : "<p>So, by your definition, you want not just a Ghost, but an Apparition: a Ghost with visible, recognizable humanlike presence.</p>\n\n<p>The XBox story was my first thought, too.</p>\n\n<p>This could indeed be a virtual one, a recording of them as in the XBox story, or even an AI, a learning system that has acquired their skills and behaviors at least in the very specific domain in which it is designed to learn.</p>\n\n<p>In the XBox case, rather than merely driving like they drove on their last lap, a learning system could drive like the drove on average, displaying random of their driving quirks; or could drive as they did at their best <em>on each stage</em> of the race, thus driving better in sum than they ever did in life.</p>\n\n<p>A recorded video of someone, projected, would also work. If holograms are possible, then you have the Star Wars \"Help me, Obi Wan Kenobe, you are my only hope!\" - a ghost of a living person perhaps. Otherwise, you can project onto a wall, or more mysteriously, a stream of smoke, mist, cloud, or water. Could also be a computer-generated sprite texture-mapped with the person's face. Particularly with a low-fidelity projection onto a vague mist, the computer-generatedness would not be so apparent.</p>\n\n<p>But there are other ways to record a person's passing. Perhaps, as they walked from a clearing, they swiped at the thick leaves, and in doing so, either deliberately or accidentally hacked out a person-shaped hole, which, when the sun sets in the evening and shines through it, illuminates the spray from the waterfall. Doesn't even have to be a hole anyone's hacked out - but more likely if done as a deliberate thing. Since the sun moves slowly, you could have it so that only when the light from the sun lit a crystal at a certain angle, it refracted to become a projector - that way you could limit it only to a few minutes, or even a few seconds.</p>\n\n<p>One effect I've seen that caused much consternation was headlights over a hill, which, because of the angle of the road, would shine in the back of a ruined house: the house would look lived in, for a moment, and then would fall dark again as the car moved on. Headlights on hilltops have also caused any number of UFO sightings. So, they make good brief-unexplained-lightings. If a picture is briefly lit by headlights passing outside, and the figure in it appears to because the shadows cast on the picture move, that could be a convincing \"ghost\" effect. Lightning could have a similar effect.</p>\n\n<p>Another good effect is a moon-halo. Here's a good trick. When the moon is close to full and dew lies upon the grass, look at your shadow: you will be surrounded by a halo. Tell your friend \"Wow, there's a halo around your shadow!\" (as if you see the halo around <em>his</em> shadow, and not your own) and the odds of him thinking there's something mystical about himself are quite high. When you stand above a mist-covered valley, and your shadow is cast onto the mists below, that has the same effect, writ large. So in this way, someone could be convinced into thinking they see, perhaps, their own ghost, or at least an outline, with a glow from their spirit?</p>\n\n<p>Double-exposure is possible, too: taking shots with a film exposed some years ago that you did not know had already been used to shoot someone else, would show them as ghosts in the shots. Similarly for a videotape with an erase/record head that did not fully wipe the previous data, perhaps.</p>\n\n<p>For more modern digital tech, it would take some kind of software bug - or a virus/malware/joke app that would impose another character into existing video.</p>\n\n<p>In realtime, augmented reality apps like google goggles or yelp's equivalent, let you point your phone at things and see signs for places nearby, etc... what is there was software on your phone that meant, when you pointed your phone camera at something, you say your dead friend superimposed in the shot, or perhaps just their face overlaid over nearby faces that the camera software identified?</p>",

		"Body" : "<p><em>Wow, what a great range of answers! Thanks everyone who has answered so far and I hope to see many more! Here's my take, after a half-day of on-off thought (also set up a few servers in-between):</em></p>\n\n<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Mind_uploading\" rel=\"nofollow\">Uploading</a> never worked. It turned out that creating a new memory-association-chain in a human brain involved a holistic effort by the entire brain, and the complexity of the process defeated the best human minds for centuries on end. All it did manage to create was an abomination, a sad simile, incapable of true consciousness, of genuinely remembering new experiences, or of adapting to new environments. A failure. </p>\n\n<p>With time, a new practice evolved, of decorating the crypts, cemeteries and cities of the dead with these holographic and magnetic-force-field projections of those no longer living, based on such partial uploads. Some were only triggered by specific actions, such as placing flowers in a particular vase in the crypt, or rippling the water in a still, crystal-clear pool, while some only activated on the anniversary of their death. The varieties were endless.</p>\n\n<p>As this became more accepted, and the projections were no longer seen as abominations, the practice grew in scope. After the massive blast that took out the Andromeda Gateway and the surrounding great city of Carston, surviving friends and relatives recreated a distorted, slowly evolving projected replica of the entire city and its millions of inhabitants from records of the town and of the people, all on top of the overgrown ruins. As a monument.</p>\n\n<p>On the <a href=\"http://worldbuilding.stackexchange.com/questions/8453/massive-murderous-destruction-also-manportable\">fierce battlefields</a> of the future, people's life-recorders sometimes survived the blast that killed their owners, and, left on the desolate and temporarily radioactive wastelands, the life-recorders triggered and released a sad and confused ghost, forever retracing their last steps and random fragments of their life. Those with <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Zero-point_energy\" rel=\"nofollow\">ZPE</a> power-plates had a lifetime measured in tens of millennia. </p>\n\n<p>Slowly, as the gap between those embracing technology and those that didn't grew, the daring, the curious, the brave and the restless grew weary of Earth and embarked in <a href=\"http://worldbuilding.stackexchange.com/questions/9022/how-to-get-across-the-galaxy-moving-slower-than-light-in-a-single-lifetime\">great journeys across space</a>, leaving behinds an ever-more conservative, ever regressing Earth. The <a href=\"http://worldbuilding.stackexchange.com/questions/8866/where-to-anchor-my-space-elevator\">long elevators</a> were torn off their sockets and cast out into space. Things that were once known, were forgotten. The great underground oil, coal and mineral manufacturers trudged on for millenia, undoing the depleting work of many centuries and creating <a href=\"http://worldbuilding.stackexchange.com/questions/8716/sapience-pulsar-could-intelligence-come-in-waves\">new resources for a new dawn</a>. Eventually even these great machines froze in their tunnels.</p>\n\n<p>The ghosts, however, lived on amid the crypts and ruins of those majestic towns of an age long forgotten.</p>",

		"Title" : "All right, maybe we can go for an algorithm!\n\ngiven the two end of the s...",
		"Body" : "<p>All right, maybe we can go for an algorithm!</p>\n\n<p>given the two end of the segment $A=(a_x,a_y),B=(b_x,b_y)$ and the three vertices of the triangle $C=(c_x,c_y),D=(d_x,d_y),E=(e_x,e_y)$</p>\n\n<p><strong>Intersection</strong> (A,B,C,D,E)</p>\n\n<p>(1) <strong>if</strong> A is in the triangle and B is not (or vice versa) \n    <strong>then</strong> <em>return</em> True</p>\n\n<p>(2) <strong>if</strong> (Intersection(A,(A+B)/2,C,D,E) <strong>or</strong> Intersection((A+B)/2,B,C,D,E))<br>\n    <strong>then</strong> <em>return</em> True <strong>else</strong> <em>return</em> False</p>\n\n<p>Here is a method to check whether a point is in a triangle using cross product <a href=\"http://www.blackpawn.com/texts/pointinpoly/\" rel=\"nofollow\">http://www.blackpawn.com/texts/pointinpoly/</a></p>\n\n<p>bad one (thanks Daryl):\nTo check if an end of the segment, say A, is in the triangle we can simply check it's coordinates against the triangle vertices ones:</p>\n\n<p>For A to be in the triangle we should have\n$min \\{c_x,d_x,e_x\\} \\leq a_x \\leq max \\{c_x,d_x,e_x\\}$ and\n$min \\{c_y,d_y,e_y\\} \\leq a_y \\leq max \\{c_y,d_y,e_y\\}$</p>",

		"Title" : "JAVA, Sehtimianer\n\nThanks again to TheBestOne, I copied his core methods...",
		"Body" : "<h2>JAVA, Sehtimianer</h2>\n\n<p>Thanks again to TheBestOne, I copied his core methods too ; )\nThis is my first time playing a KingOfTheHill-CodeGame, so I hope I did everything right.\nI proudly present the Sehtimianers :D</p>\n\n<pre><code>import java.io.BufferedReader;\nimport java.io.BufferedWriter;\nimport java.io.File;\nimport java.io.FileReader;\nimport java.io.FileWriter;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.util.ArrayList;\nimport java.util.Collections;\nimport java.util.HashMap;\nimport java.util.List;\nimport java.util.Map;\n\npublic class Sehtimianer {\n\nprivate static final String FILENAME = \"Sehtimianer.txt\";\nprivate static final int AGGRESSIVE_ROUND_BORDER = 80;\n\nint round;\nint playerID;\nint thisTownID;\n\nList<Town> towns = new ArrayList<Town>();\nList<Town> myTowns = new ArrayList<Town>();\nList<Town> playerTowns = new ArrayList<Town>();\nList<Town> neutralTowns = new ArrayList<Town>();\nMap<Integer, Integer> townToPlayerMapping = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();\nboolean isAllowedToWriteMapping = true;\n\nTown thisTown;\n\npublic static void main(String[] args) {\n    if (args.length == 0) {\n        // new File(FILENAME).delete();\n        System.out.println(\"100 100 100\");\n        return;\n    }\n    new Sehtimianer().decide(args[0].split(\";\"));\n}\n\nprivate void decide(String[] args) {\n    // final long start = System.currentTimeMillis();\n\n    round = Integer.parseInt(args[0]);\n    playerID = Integer.parseInt(args[1]);\n    thisTownID = Integer.parseInt(args[2]);\n\n    for (int i = 3; i < args.length; i++) {\n        towns.add(new Town(args[i]));\n    }\n\n    for (Town town : towns) {\n        if (town.isMine()) {\n            myTowns.add(town);\n            if (town.isThisTown()) {\n                thisTown = town;\n            }\n        } else {\n            if (town.getOwner() == -1) {\n                neutralTowns.add(town);\n            } else {\n                playerTowns.add(town);\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    if (new File(FILENAME).exists()) {\n        try {\n            BufferedReader reader = new BufferedReader(new FileReader(FILENAME));\n            String inputLine;\n            String[] ids;\n            while ((inputLine = reader.readLine()) != null) {\n                ids = inputLine.split(\";\");\n                if (ids.length == 1) {\n                    Integer writingTownID = Integer.valueOf(ids[0]);\n                    boolean townIsLost = true;\n                    for (Town town : myTowns) {\n                        if (town.getId() == writingTownID) {\n                            townIsLost = false;\n                            break;\n                        }\n                    }\n                    isAllowedToWriteMapping = townIsLost || thisTownID == writingTownID;\n                    continue;\n                }\n                townToPlayerMapping.put(Integer.valueOf(ids[0]), Integer.valueOf(ids[1]));\n            }\n            reader.close();\n\n            for (Town town : towns) {\n                if (!townToPlayerMapping.get(town.getId()).equals(town.getOwner())) {\n                    town.setDefenseBonus(false);\n                }\n            }\n        } catch (IOException e) {\n            // Dont worry : )\n        }\n    }\n\n    if (round == 1) {\n        int maxKnights = 0;\n        int maxKnightTownID = thisTownID;\n        for (Town town : myTowns) {\n            if (town == thisTown) {\n                continue;\n            }\n            if (town.knightCount() > maxKnights) {\n                maxKnights = town.knightCount();\n                maxKnightTownID = town.getId();\n            }\n        }\n        if (maxKnightTownID != thisTownID) {\n            System.out.println(\"S \" + maxKnightTownID + \" \" + thisTown.knightCount());\n        }\n    } else if (round % 3 == 2) {\n        int myKnightIncome = 0;\n        for (Town town : myTowns) {\n            myKnightIncome += town.lowbornCount() / 2;\n        }\n\n        Map<Integer, Integer> playerKnightIncomeMap = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();\n        Map<Integer, Integer> playerTownCountMap = new HashMap<Integer, Integer>();\n        List<Integer> nextRoundKnights = new ArrayList<Integer>();\n        Map<Integer, Town> nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping = new HashMap<Integer, Town>();\n\n        for (Town town : playerTowns) {\n            fillDescisionMaps(town, nextRoundKnights, nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping, playerKnightIncomeMap, playerTownCountMap);\n        }\n        for (Town town : neutralTowns) {\n            fillDescisionMaps(town, nextRoundKnights, nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping, playerKnightIncomeMap, playerTownCountMap);\n        }\n\n        Integer maxEnemyKnightIncome = 0;\n        for (Integer knightIncome : playerKnightIncomeMap.values()) {\n            if (knightIncome > maxEnemyKnightIncome) {\n                maxEnemyKnightIncome = knightIncome;\n            }\n        }\n        Integer maxEnemyTownCount = 0;\n        for (Integer townCount : playerTownCountMap.values()) {\n            if (townCount > maxEnemyTownCount) {\n                maxEnemyTownCount = townCount;\n            }\n        }\n\n        if (maxEnemyKnightIncome > myKnightIncome || (round > AGGRESSIVE_ROUND_BORDER && maxEnemyTownCount >= myTowns.size())) {\n            Collections.sort(nextRoundKnights);\n            int possibleHighest = 0;\n            Town enemyTown;\n            int enemyTownUpkeep;\n            for (int i = nextRoundKnights.size() - 1; i >= 0; i--) {\n                possibleHighest = nextRoundKnights.get(i);\n                enemyTown = nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping.get(possibleHighest);\n                enemyTownUpkeep = enemyTown.lowbornCount() / 2;\n                if (enemyTownUpkeep > (possibleHighest - enemyTownUpkeep)) { // Substract the calculated Income for the next Turn\n                    // Town will be lost because of revolution after captured -> Bad target\n                    possibleHighest = 0;\n                    continue;\n                }\n                if (round > AGGRESSIVE_ROUND_BORDER || enemyTown.lowbornCount() > 0) {\n                    break;\n                }\n            }\n            if (possibleHighest > 0) {\n                Town attackedTown = nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping.get(possibleHighest);\n                System.out.println(\"A \" + attackedTown.getId() + \" \" + calcHowMuchKnightsShouldAttack(attackedTown, possibleHighest));\n            }\n        }\n    }\n\n    if (isAllowedToWriteMapping) {\n        try {\n            BufferedWriter writer = new BufferedWriter(new FileWriter(FILENAME));\n            writer.write(thisTownID + \"\\n\");\n            for (Town town : towns) {\n                writer.write(town.getId() + \";\" + town.getOwner() + \"\\n\");\n            }\n            writer.close();\n        } catch (IOException e) {\n            // Dont worry : )\n        }\n    }\n\n    System.out.println(\"W\");\n\n    // long duration = System.currentTimeMillis() - start;\n    // if (duration > 1000) {\n    // throw new RuntimeException();\n    // }\n}\n\nprivate void fillDescisionMaps(Town town, List<Integer> nextRoundKnights, Map<Integer, Town> nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping, Map<Integer, Integer> playerKnightIncomeMap,\n        Map<Integer, Integer> playerTownCountMap) {\n    int calculatedKnights = calcKnightsInNextRound(town);\n    nextRoundKnights.add(calculatedKnights);\n    nextRoundKnightsToTownMapping.put(calculatedKnights, town);\n\n    Integer enemyKnightIncome = playerKnightIncomeMap.get(town.getOwner());\n    if (enemyKnightIncome == null) {\n        enemyKnightIncome = town.lowbornCount() / 2;\n    } else {\n        enemyKnightIncome = enemyKnightIncome + (town.lowbornCount() / 2);\n    }\n    playerKnightIncomeMap.put(town.getOwner(), enemyKnightIncome);\n\n    Integer enemyTownCount = playerTownCountMap.get(town.getOwner());\n    if (enemyTownCount == null) {\n        enemyTownCount = Integer.valueOf(1);\n    } else {\n        enemyTownCount = enemyTownCount + 1;\n    }\n    playerTownCountMap.put(town.getOwner(), enemyTownCount);\n}\n\nprivate int calcKnightsInNextRound(Town enemyTown) {\n    int knights = (int) ((double) enemyTown.knightCount() * (enemyTown.isDefenseBonus() ? 1.2 : 1));\n    knights = thisTown.getFreeKnights() - knights;\n    if (knights > 0) {\n        knights += enemyTown.lowbornCount() / 2;\n    } else {\n        knights = 0;\n    }\n    return knights;\n}\n\nprivate int calcHowMuchKnightsShouldAttack(Town enemyTown, int possibleHighest) {\n    if (round < AGGRESSIVE_ROUND_BORDER && thisTown.lowbornCount() == 0) {\n        return thisTown.knightCount();\n    }\n\n    int spareKnights = possibleHighest - enemyTown.lowbornCount(); // Correct -> div 2 and mul 2\n    int minShouldSend = thisTown.getFreeKnights() - (spareKnights / 2);\n\n    return Math.max(minShouldSend, thisTown.knightCount() / 2);\n}\n\nprivate class Town {\n    private final int ownerId;\n    private final int id;\n    private final int knights;\n    private final int lowborns;\n    private boolean defenseBonus;\n\n    public Town(String string) {\n        String[] args = string.split(\"_\");\n        ownerId = Integer.parseInt(args[0]);\n        id = Integer.parseInt(args[1]);\n        knights = Integer.parseInt(args[2]);\n        lowborns = Integer.parseInt(args[3]);\n        defenseBonus = true;\n    }\n\n    public boolean isDefenseBonus() {\n        return defenseBonus;\n    }\n\n    public void setDefenseBonus(boolean defenseBonus) {\n        this.defenseBonus = defenseBonus;\n    }\n\n    public int getId() {\n        return id;\n    }\n\n    public int getOwner() {\n        return ownerId;\n    }\n\n    public int knightCount() {\n        return knights;\n    }\n\n    public int lowbornCount() {\n        return lowborns;\n    }\n\n    public boolean isMine() {\n        return ownerId == playerID;\n    }\n\n    public boolean isThisTown() {\n        return id == thisTownID;\n    }\n\n    private int getFreeKnights() {\n        return knights - lowborns / 2 - 1;\n    }\n}\n}\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>The Sehtimianers try to be superior the whole game and finish it at the end.\nI hope my bot won't do too bad : )</p>",

		"Title" : "Brownie Questions",
		"Body" : "<p>For the last couple of times that I have baked brownies, they would come out with a thin layer of oil at the top. I don't know if i'm not giving the butter-sugar mixture enough time to cool down but after I in the egg and chocolate, the batter looks too runny and oily.\nFirst Method: Melt butter and sugar together in a pot until homogeneous, add beaten egg then chocolate. Put all of that together with the dry ingredients and bake.</p>\n\n<p>Recently, I tried doing something a little bit different. I've been making caramels, so I kind of experimented with my sugar.\nNew Method: Melt sugar until it becomes a syrup, then add hot melted butter until it becomes homogeneous. 		"Title" : "No idea about Joomla or the restrictions you may be dealing with on a VM...",
		"Body" : "<p>No idea about Joomla or the restrictions you may be dealing with on a VM, but how about something like:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /data/www\nsudo chmod -R g+rws /data/www\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>That recursively sets the user:group to www-data:www-data using chown, and g+s part of the chown statement will ensure that files written by any permitted user maintain the owner's group (GUID). The r and w are the usual read and write permissions.</p>\n\n<p>That's what I use on Ubuntu/Apache, but I believe that it's also possible to do the same with the user (SUID). Maybe someone else can chip in if I have the syntax wrong, but I believe something like:</p>\n\n<pre><code>sudo chown -R www-data:www-data /data/www\nsudo chmod -R ug+rws /data/www\n</code></pre>\n\n<p>will set read/write for user and group only, and force files to have the www-data:www-data user:group.</p>\n\n<p>However, read up on SUID and GUID, as by doing this you're granting other users the permissions of www-data. The other caveat is that if your drive is mounted with the nosuid flag set, none of this will work.</p>",

		"Title" : "how about using unit circle? \n\nfirst let us deal with the the first quad...",
		"Body" : "<p>how about using unit circle? </p>\n\n<p>first let us deal with the the first quadrant. we will pick two points $A = (x,y), B = (y,x)$ on the unit circle in the first quadrant. the two points are images of each other on the mirror along the line $y = x$ let us also label the points $P = (1,0), Q = (0,1)$</p>\n\n<p>we will need the following two thins:</p>\n\n<p>(a) $arc PA$ = arc QB,$</p>\n\n<p>(b) $arc PB + arc PA = \\pi/2.$</p>\n\n<p>let us use the definition, you can see how the name is apt,<br>\n$\\arcsin y = \\arccos x = arc PA$ where $A = (x, y)$ is a point on the unit circle. </p>\n\n<p>using the above definition $$\\arccos x = arc AP, \\arcsin x = arc BP,  \\arccos x + \\arcsin x = arc AP + arc BP = \\pi/2 $$</p>\n\n<p>the range of $\\arccos$ is $[0, \\pi]$ and of $\\arcsin$ is $[-\\pi/2, \\pi/2]$. so that when you have negative argument for $arccos$ the point in the second quadrant, and for $\\arcsin$ is in the fourth quadrant.</p>",

	{
		"ReportLink" : "http://chat.meta.stackexchange.com/transcript/message/2953553",
		"PostUrl" : "http://physics.stackexchange.com/a/161094",
		"Site" : "physics.stackexchange.com",
		"Title" : "Magnetocrystalline anisotropy is all about spontaneous magnetization. Co...",
		"Body" : "<p><a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Magnetocrystalline_anisotropy\" rel=\"nofollow\">Magnetocrystalline anisotropy</a> is all about spontaneous magnetization. Considere a (single domain) ferromagnetic material. Depending on its crystal structure, its spontaneous magnetization will tend to be aligned with a direction that minimize the interaction energy between magnetic dipoles carried by the atoms contained in one <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Crystal_structure\" rel=\"nofollow\">unit cell</a> of the lattice.</p>\n\n<p>That's why, depending on the geometry of the lattice system, you will have different types of magnetic anisotropy : uniaxial (one single easy axe), cubic (2 axes, one easy and one hard), tetragonal, etc.</p>\n\n<p>So far, the most common anisotropy one can meet is the uniaxial one, that is particulary useful for the <a href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Stoner%E2%80%93Wohlfarth_model\" rel=\"nofollow\">Stoner-Wohlfarth model</a>.</p>\n\n<p>Now, how about when an external magnetic field is applied? Well, there are two kind of energies in competition : the anisotropy energy which is minimum when the magnetization is along the direction of the easy axis, and the Zeeman energy which is the interaction energy between the magnetization and the external field. This situation is well described by the Stoner-Wohlfarth model and consists basically in minimizing the energy of the ferromagnetic system :\n$$\n\\mathrm{E}(\\theta,\\phi)=K\\sin^2\\theta-\\mu_0M_sH\\cos(\\theta-\\phi)\n$$\nThe first term is the anisotropy energy ($\\theta$ being the angle between the easy axis and the magnetization, and $K$ the anisotropy strength), the second correspond to the Zeeman energy ($H$ is the norm of the applied magnetic field and $\\phi$ the angle that it forms with the easy axis).</p>\n\n<p>For convinience, let be $\\phi=\\pi$ fixed as an example. Then the energy $\\mathrm{E}$ has to be minimize according to the variable $\\theta$. In dimensionless units, one have :\n$$\n\\mathrm{e}(\\theta)=\\frac{1}{K}\\,\\mathrm{E}(\\theta,\\phi=\\pi)=\\sin^2\\theta+2h\\cos\\theta\\quad\\text{with}\\quad h=\\frac{\\mu_0M_sH}{2K}\n$$\nOne can easily find the equilibrium states $\\theta_{\\mathrm{eq}}$ by computing $\\partial_\\theta\\,\\mathrm{e}(\\theta=\\theta_{\\mathrm{eq}})=0$ :\n$$\n\\theta_{\\mathrm{eq}}\\equiv\\{0,\\pi,\\theta_h=\\arccos(h)\\}\n$$\nand then study their stability by looking at the sign of the quantity $\\partial^2_\\theta\\,\\mathrm{e}(\\theta=\\theta_{\\mathrm{eq}})$, namely :\n$$\n\\partial^2_\\theta\\,\\mathrm{e}(\\theta=0)=2(1-h)\n$$\n$$\n\\partial^2_\\theta\\,\\mathrm{e}(\\theta=\\pi)=2(1+h)\n$$\n$$\n\\partial^2_\\theta\\,\\mathrm{e}(\\theta=\\theta_h)=2(h^2-1)\n$$\nThe take home message here is that it is possible to change the stability of the different equilibrium solutions by varying the magnitude $H$ of the magnetic field, i.e. by varying $h$. By changing $h$, one can actually <strong>flip</strong> the magnetization from one equilibrium orientation to another.</p>",

		"Title" : "Going in a slightly different direction: don't go overboard. Most small-...",
		"Body" : "<p>Going in a slightly different direction: don't go overboard. Most small-time prisons probably have a few minor defenses against spellcasters. They'll have their stuff taken, they'll be behind iron bars, if the jailor expects them to be spellcasters he\u00B4ll wear earplugs and hang the key on a 20 pound weight so it can't be Mage Handed and it\u00B4ll probably be dark, which makes vision targeting hard. Other than that; maybe a double set of doors with different keys, so that a single charm won't help, and a number of guards with orders to kill anyone who tries anything funny.</p>\n\n<p>If you go above and beyond this kind of thing for a general kind of prison, then you are basically unfairly targeting wizards. Most Wizards, especially the kind that you'd find in a low-level prison, will be contained by the above. If they try anything funny, they get stabbed to death by the guards. Most would probably not even <em>try</em> to escape. For every guard you charm, there's 5 more with pointy weapons.</p>\n\n<p>Remember: many characters have a glib tongue and can talk their way out of a prison. We don't go around asking \"how do you keep a silver tongued rogue in prison?\". We don't ask \"How do you keep a barbarian who can bend the bars in prison?\", even though they probably can when in a Rage.</p>\n\n<p>If the wizard is high level and in a small-town prison <em>he will be able to escape.</em> So will any other high level character put in that situation; it's not a Wizard problem as much as it's a high level character vs low level challenge problem.</p>\n\n<p>Now of course when it comes to special anti-powerful-wizard-prisons, you can go all out, but those are fantastical locations, not simple buildings designed to hold not so powerful people.</p>",

Cutting down on where the fly can go will allow you to kill is more easily.  It is also helpful, if you can shoo in into another room, to pick a room that contains lighter colors.  It is very difficult to see a fly against a dark background. 		"Body" : "<p>Okay so I finally figured this out. It was a stupid mistake on my part. The files I had in the specified folders were actually feature classes and not datasets. Anyway it is not possible to create a dataset inside a folder. It can only be done inside a geodatabase. So for someone who knows their way around with ArcGIS, they could have noticed that I had just a folder in the code but I was calling <code>ListDataSets()</code> function which is wrong. Using <code>ListFeatureClasses()</code> solved the issue and the files were properly reprojected. Thanks for all the inputs.</p>",
